<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-160-522  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 160 522.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 3 1989 n242 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MCI, legion of companies battle FTS data mandate. (MCICommunications Corp - Federal Telecommunications System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jackson, Kelly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>MCI Communications Corp is spearheading the Congressional lobby tooverturn the bill requiring federal agencies to use FTS-2000 forall voice and data traffic.andP;  MCI argues that only switched-voiceservice, and not data, is covered by the legislation.andP;  MCI andseveral major systems-integration and data communicationscompanies are concerned about losing the federal market and themillions of dollars they have invested in their bids for currentand future contracts which the FTS-2000 could take over.andP;  IBM andUnisys Corp fear that the two FTS-2000 contractors, ATandamp;T and USSprint Communications Co, will become the exclusive suppliers offederal agencies' data products.andP;  Congressional sources howeversay that MCI's interpretation of the bill is incorrect.andP;  Officialsof the General Services Administration, administrator of theFTS-2000 project, admit the need to clarify the mandatory-useprovision.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (telecommunication policy).andO;Ticker:    MCIC.andO;Topic:     LegislationLobbyingTelecommunicationsCommunications Service SuppliersGovernment RegulationFederal Telecommunications SystemPurchasing SystemsCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>